DOT Traffic Speeds¶

About the data¶

There are over 49 million rows in this dataset.

Though a csv is available for download, accessing the data of interest via the API is the better choice when exploring a subset.

A useful metadata doc describes the purpose of this dataset:

New York City DOTs traffic speed detector feed is a free service that allows various user groups (i.e. the general public, private sector, commercial vendors, transportation agencies, researchers, media and others) to download traffic speed information on a regular basis to use in their applications and research efforts. This data feed contains 'realtime' traffic information from locations where NYCDOT has installed sensors, mostly on major arterials and highways within the City limits. NYCDOT uses this information for emergency response and management.

Read the data¶

I will demonstrate how to modify the "grab and go" API code into something that reads only a subset.

DOT offers a helpful API doc with "grab and go code" to read a subset into a pandas DataFrame.

In [1]:
# download libraries
import pandas as pd
from sodapy import Socrata
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# First 20 results, returned as JSON from API / converted to Python list of
# dictionaries by sodapy.
results = client.get(dataset_identifier=socrata_dataset_identifier, limit=5)

# Convert to pandas DataFrame
results_df = pd.DataFrame.from_records(results)

There are 12 columns, described in more detail in the metadata doc. Right away I know I can drop the status and transcom_id fields from this DataFrame.

The sodapy.Socrata.client.get() method allows filtering of queries.

Dataset challenge: size and cardinality¶

The size of this dataset and the number of distinct values in each column presents a challenge when attempting to identify a subset. Prior to filtering this dataset, I received timeout errors. Before I attempt to create a pandas DataFrame from a subset, I will use sodapy to determine the number of distinct values in the link_name column.

Like pandas, sodapy allows exploration of data.

I will use my app token to read a subset of data: the Cross Bronx Expressway beginning at E Taylor Avenue and ending at Castle Hill Avenue. I am requesting date in descending order so that I can see the 150,000 most recent records. I found that increasing the limit of records beyond this led to a timeout error. For reference, the Google Maps image below shows the length of the link, the distance in miles, and the approximate time to travel according to Google.

In [12]:
client = Socrata(socrata_domain, socrata_token, "snr131@gmail.com", "kULHSiw6TF2UjxN")
results = client.get(dataset_identifier=socrata_dataset_identifier, limit=150000,
                     select="SPEED, TRAVEL_TIME, DATA_AS_OF, BOROUGH, LINK_NAME", 
                     where="LINK_NAME == 'CBE E TAYLOR AVENUE - CASTLE HILL AVENUE'", order="DATA_AS_OF DESC")

In [41]:
# split the timestamp into hour, month, day of week, and year
time = results_df['DATA_AS_OF']
results_df['HOUR'] = results_df['DATA_AS_OF'].apply(lambda time: time.hour)
results_df['DAY_OF_WEEK'] = results_df['DATA_AS_OF'].apply(lambda time: time.dayofweek)
results_df['MONTH'] = results_df['DATA_AS_OF'].apply(lambda time: time.month)
results_df['YEAR'] = results_df['DATA_AS_OF'].apply(lambda time: time.year)

Predictive analysis using scikit-learn¶

In [47]:
# import libraries
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

Split the data into training and testing sets¶

In [53]:
dependent = results_df[['TRAVEL_TIME']]
independent_without_speed = results_df[['HOUR','DAY_OF_WEEK','MONTH']]
independent_with_speed = results_df[['HOUR','DAY_OF_WEEK','MONTH', 'SPEED']]

Create and evaluate models¶

Without speed¶

When speed is excluded from the model, it predicts travel time correctly on 0.2% of the test set.

In [49]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(independent_without_speed, dependent, test_size=0.2, random_state=1)
In [50]:
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
